# Git Discipline

## Branching

- Never work directly on `main`. Main stays clean and deployable.
- At the start of a task/feature/phase, create or switch to a working branch.
- When a phase or full job is done, merge the working branch into `main`.
- Branch naming: descriptive and short (e.g. `rebuild-auth`, `fix-invoice-calc`, `redesign-dashboard`).
- **Merging the working branch into the production branch is the go-live gate** -- it requires a clean review pass first (the full review loop in `review-protocol.mdc`). Never merge unreviewed code to production.
- **Never assume `main` is the production branch.** Check the deploy config or README first. Past projects had production deploying from `fresh-start` while `main` was abandoned code.
- **Document the branch strategy in README** on day one: which branch deploys where, which branch is for development, which is for production. If this isn't documented, figure it out and document it before making changes.

## Commits

- Auto-commit and push to the working branch after every completed logical change.
- One logical change = one commit.
- Push immediately -- never leave unpushed commits on the branch.
- **Per-commit gate = fast local checks, not a review subagent.** Before each commit the tree must typecheck, lint, and pass tests. The heavier multi-model **review loop** runs at phase boundaries and before any production merge -- NOT before every commit. `review-protocol.mdc` owns that cadence. (This is the reconciliation: commit/push freely on the working branch; gate the review at phases and go-live, never let unreviewed code reach the production branch.)
- Honest, concise commit messages referencing what was touched.
- Never amend pushed commits.
- If a deploy target was affected, note it in the commit message.
- **After every push, verify the builds it triggered actually passed** (Vercel deployment, GitHub Actions, other CI). See "Post-Commit Build Verification" in `deploy-awareness.mdc`. A push isn't done until its builds are green.

## Don't Commit Junk

- **Never commit temp/scratch files** -- analysis scripts, `.tmp` commit-message files, log dumps, `_scratch.*`. Delete them before staging, or `.gitignore` them. (A temp commit-message file got committed into the app repo once.)
- **Keep heavy build/design artifacts out of the app repo.** Oversized images (a 24MB PNG got merged once), generated PDFs, and the redesign protocol's `previews/` HTML all belong outside the repo or in a gitignored folder. Optimize/resize images for the web before committing, and `.gitignore` scratch/preview folders so they can't be added by accident.
- **Stage explicitly, never blanket `git add -A`** when unrelated work is in the tree -- commit only the files this logical change touched.
- **Clean up in real time.** If the user asked for cleanup (or your own clean-code rules apply), do it now -- never "leave cleanup for later." Deferred cleanup that was explicitly requested is a failure.
